    ),
    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided financial disclosures, here is a detailed breakdown of the company\'s segment reporting, revenue and cost structures, intercompany eliminations, and the specific economics of the Starlink (Connectivity) and xAI (AI) segments.\n\n### 1. Segment Reporting Overview\nSpaceX operates and reports financial results across three primary segments:\n*   **Space Segment:** Designs, manufactures, and launches reusable rockets (Falcon 9, Falcon Heavy, Starship, Dragon) to provide high-cadence, reliable, and affordable access to space.\n*   **Connectivity Segment:** Operates a worldwide high-speed, low-latency broadband network powered by thousands of Low-Earth Orbit Starlink satellites, serving consumer, enterprise, and government customers.\n*   **AI Segment:** Operates a vertically integrated AI platform, including the frontier LLM "Grok," AI solutions, and "X" (a real-time information and digital platform).\n\n### 2. Segment Revenue & Recognition Policies\n*   **Space Segment:** Revenue is derived from *Launch Services* (fixed-price contracts ranging from 1–5 years, recognized at a **point in time** upon payload launch/deployment) and *Launch and Development* (fixed-price contracts ranging from 1–14 years, recognized **over time** using the cost-to-cost input method).\n*   **Connectivity Segment:** Generates revenue from broadband/mobile connectivity services (recognized **over time** as services are consumed; generally month-to-month for consumers and multi-year for enterprise/mobile), Starlink Kits (recognized upon **delivery or installation**), and Starshield government contracts (recognized **over time** using cost-to-cost).\n*   **AI Segment:** Generates revenue from advertising on the X platform (recognized when delivered/engaged), premium subscriptions for X and Grok (recognized **ratably** over the subscription term), data licensing (recognized **ratably** over the contract period), and API services. Advertising revenue experiences seasonality, peaking in Q4.\n\n### 3. Segment Cost of Revenue\n*   **Connectivity:** Includes depreciation (launch, satellite, and ground infrastructure), Starlink Kit costs, shipping and handling, ground operating expenses, engineering/operations employee compensation, payment processor fees, warranty expenses, inventory excess/obsolescence, and customs/duties. \n*   **AI:** Primarily driven by infrastructure and cloud computing costs.\n*   **Space:** Includes direct launch costs and depreciation. The company notes that increased reusability of Falcon launch vehicles has driven cost efficiencies and lowered depreciation expenses in this segment.\n\n### 4. Intercompany Revenue Elimination & The Seller Segment\n*   **The Seller Segment:** The **Space segment** acts as the internal seller/provider of launch services, allocating a significant amount of its launch capacity to the Connectivity segment (for Starlink satellites) and planning future allocations to the AI segment.\n*   **Intercompany Elimination:** The company **does not recognize any inter-segment revenue** for these internal launches. Instead of recording revenue in the Space segment and an expense in the Connectivity/AI segments, the launch costs are eliminated and directly **capitalized** into "satellites in Property, plant, and equipment, net" on the consolidated balance sheet. Consequently, the Space segment\'s reported revenue strictly reflects external customer launches and activities.\n\n### 5. Starlink (Connectivity) Segment Economics\nThe Connectivity segment is a highly profitable, rapidly scaling growth engine for the company.\n*   **Financial Performance (2025):** Generated **$11,387 million** in revenue, **$4,423 million** in income from operations, and **$7,168 million** in Segment Adjusted EBITDA. This represents year-over-year growth of 49.8%, 120.4%, and 86.2%, respectively.\n*   **Key Performance Indicators (2025):** Reached **8.9 million** Starlink subscribers (up from 4.4 million in 2024). Average Revenue Per User (ARPU) was **$81/month** (down from $91 in 2024), primarily due to international expansion and the introduction of lower-priced service plans.\n*   **Economic Outlook:** Growth is driven by consumer subscriber expansion, enterprise/mobile adoption, and government (Starshield) contracts. The company expects Cost of Revenue and R&D to increase in absolute dollars but **decrease as a percentage of revenue** due to economies of scale, network efficiencies, and next-generation satellite/hardware improvements. SG&A is expected to tick up in 2026 due to targeted marketing spend.\n\n### 6. xAI (AI) Segment Economics\nThe AI segment is in a heavy investment and growth-capture phase, currently operating at a significant loss due to massive infrastructure build-outs.\n*   **Financial Performance (2025):** Generated **$3,201 million** in revenue, a **loss from operations of $(6,355) million**, and Segment Adjusted EBITDA of **$(1,237) million**. \n*   **Key Performance Indicators (2025):** Nameplate compute draw reached **0.8 gigawatts** (up from 0.3 GW in 2024), reflecting massive data center expansions.\n*   **Economic Outlook:** The segment prioritizes growth and investment in AI applications and compute infrastructure over near-term profitability. The massive operating losses are primarily driven by exorbitant Research & Development expenses (which surged to $3.8 billion+ in 2025), specifically the **depreciation of GPU hardware**, cloud computing costs, and AI data center expansion. Revenue is diversifying across X platform ads, Grok/X subscriptions, and enterprise data licensing.',
