hrough the Space segment\'s Cost of Revenue. \n*   Instead, the costs associated with launching Starlink satellites are **capitalized within the Connectivity segment** as "satellites in *Property, plant, and equipment, net*."\n*   These capitalized costs are then depreciated over time within the Connectivity segment. \n*   This policy means that as internal Starlink launch cadence increases, launch operations and overhead costs are shifted out of the Space segment and absorbed as depreciation expenses in the Connectivity segment.\n\n### 4. Segment Reporting Policy & Key Business Metrics\nThe company reports its financial performance across three primary segments: **Space, Connectivity, and AI**. Standard financial metrics (Revenue, Cost of Revenue, R&D, SG&A, Operating Income/Loss, and Segment Adjusted EBITDA) are tracked for each. \n\nHowever, because inter-segment revenue eliminations suppress the Space segment\'s financial top line, management relies on **supplemental operational metrics** to accurately measure the segment\'s true scale, throughput, and scalability:\n*   **Mass to Orbit:** The total kilograms of payload successfully deployed to orbit. This includes internal Starlink satellites, customer payloads, and development cargo. (e.g., Mass to orbit grew from 1,210 metric tons in 2023 to 2,213 metric tons in 2025, heavily driven by internal payloads).\n*   **Total Launches:** The total number of successful missions, which the company explicitly breaks down into "customer launches" versus "internal launches" to provide transparency into capacity allocation.\n\nBy tracking these operational metrics alongside financial data, the company demonstrates that the Space segment\'s infrastructure and launch economics (driven by Falcon 9 reusability and future Starship commercialization) are scaling rapidly, even if inter-segment accounting policies prevent that scale from being fully reflected in Space segment revenue.',
